HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1424
By Helton-Haynes
A RESOLUTION to recognize Susan Bedwell on the occasion of
her retirement.
WHEREAS, it is appropriate that the members of this General Assembly should honor
those citizens who have performed with uncommon devotion and enthusiasm throughout their
years of public service; and
WHEREAS, Susan Bedwell is one such estimable individual, who, having rendered fifty
years of sterling service to the Hamilton County Trustee office, has taken her much-deserved
retirement; and
WHEREAS, Ms. Bedwell began her career at the Hamilton County Trustee office on
April 1, 1976, at the age of seventeen, because her uncle, Bill Knowles, believed she did not
need an idle summer after completing her senior credits at Brainerd High School; and
WHEREAS, Susan Bedwell was hired and remained a trusted employee of the Trustee
office until her retirement in April 2026; during her distinguished career, she served under three
trustees: Bill Nobles for twenty-six years, Carl Levi for eight, and Bill Hullander for sixteen; and
WHEREAS, Susan Bedwell has served the office in a number of capacities, including in
the delinquent tax, tax relief, and accounting divisions; and
WHEREAS, Ms. Bedwell has left a lasting impact on the Trustee office and has seen
many changes over the years, including the implementation of several technical, procedural,
and customer-related improvements, which were guided by her expertise and presence; and
WHEREAS, throughout her estimable career, Susan Bedwell demonstrated the utmost
professionalism, ability, and integrity, winning the unbridled respect and admiration of her
colleagues and the community alike; now, therefore,
HJR1424
016523
- 1 -

BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we extend to Susan Bedwell our heartfelt wishes for a happy and fulfilling
retirement and every continued success in her future endeavors.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
